Engine.enginePackage

Class EngineLogger

  • java.lang.Object
    • Engine.enginePackage.TreeLogger
      • Engine.enginePackage.EngineLogger

  • public final class EngineLogger
extends TreeLogger
    An extension of the TreeLogger with custom messages. A message type is used to identify the different messages the engine may log.

    Each method of this class inserts a message of a different type.

    Some methods only inserts a new message, and some other methods additionally set the current node as the newly created one. Methods setting the current node have suffix Msg. Methods not setting the current node have suffix MsgChild.

    By convention the message type is stored at the first position in the message.

    This class provide a mechanism for avoiding generation off all the data. Descendants of nodes of types in the frontierTypes set are cut, to avoid the overhead of storing all the logged nodes.

    Also logging can be turned off at all by calling TreeLogger.setLogging(boolean) with false.

    If it is needed to collect all the nodes in a branch, including descendants of the nodes in the frontierTypes set, it is possible to specify the specific branches that must be fully collected. This is done through the collectables queue, where requests should be inserted. It is needed, then, that the Engine execution generating the requested branches be executed again, so the logger can do its work.

    The requested branches will be returned in the compressed queue. Each entry in this queue holds a a branch identifier and a bunch of consecutive nodes of the log tree. The branch identifier is the index of its root, which will always be a child of the log tree root. The bunch of nodes starts at the beginning of the first branch requested and ends somewhere in the branch identified in this entry. This identified branch is guaranteed to be between the first requested branch and the last.

    The reason to have an entry in the compressed queue that does not contain all the requested nodes is that they could be too many, and therefore have to be collected in stages. Execution of the engine will be suspended if this happens, and will be resumed after the caller gets rid of the first chunk of data.

    When collecting full branches, the nodes in every other branch will be discarded. The method setBranchCounter(int) can be used to indicate at which branch execution of the Engine will start.
